ed to the challenge of the border in British North America and post-Confederation Canada. For nearly a century, officials ranging from high court judges to local police officers embraced the ethos of transnational enforcement of criminal law. By focusing on common criminals, escaped slaves, and political refugees, Miller reveals a period of legal genesis where both formal and informal legal regimes were established across northern North America and around the world to extradite and abduct fugitives. Miller also reveals how the law remained confused, amorphous, and often ineffectual at confronting the threat of the border to the rule of law. This engrossing history will be of interest to legal, political, and intellectual historians alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCriminal lawxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aCriminal lawxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aCriminal lawxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aCriminal lawxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCriminal lawzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCriminal lawzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCriminal lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCriminal lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aExtraditionzCanadaxHistory. 0aExtraditionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFugitives from justicezCanadaxHistory. 0aFugitives from justicezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSovereigntyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aThe Osgoode Society, , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751283540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487512835423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487512835.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press 